=A0
Not exactly. Awakening is just a step towards freedom. Freedom comes in=
 the end after walking a path for enough time after awakening.
=C2=A0
An un=
awakened sadhaka practicing jnana yoga reads books and talks eloquently abo=
ut how everything is god, but looks at different people, objects and experi=
ences with a different attitude. He becomes happy (if not externally, atlea=
st internally) when people praise him and becomes upset when people critici=
ze him, and so on. An awakened sadhaka practicing jnana yoga starts to hone=
stly contemplate one's actions, words, thoughts (and even instincts finally=
) and slowly weeds out conditioning that makes one look at different transi=
ent things differently. As his equanimity increases, still there will be ep=
isodes of getting carried away. As he employs contemplation and self-correc=
tion more and more, such episodes will become less and less frequent and on=
e will become liberated in the end.
=C2=A0
An unawakened sadhaka practicing=
 karma yoga passionately engages in dharmik actions for the benefit of othe=
rs. He gets elated and feels proud when good results come and becomes upset=
 when bad results come. An awakened sadhaka practicing karma yoga starts to=
 have detachment to results. When something happens which makes him elated,=
 proud, ashamed or upset, he will not think much about it, take it as god's=
 prasad and think about what is the right action for him right now. As his =
detachment increases, still there will be episodes of getting carried away.=
 As one becomes more and more detached (to results of actions), such episod=
es will become less and less frequent and one will become liberated in the =
end.
=C2=A0
An unawakened sadhaka practicing raja yoga goes through yama, n=
iyama, pratyahara, dhyana, dharana etc. His psychic life force may even ari=
se and ascend. He may have various experiences and may feel proud or become=
 attached to them. An awakened sadhaka practicing raja yoga will not not lo=
se self-control in the face of anything and will keep the focus on samadhi.=
 He will not be distracted by anything that comes on the way and keep perfe=
cting concentration and self-control so that samadhi (deep concentration on=
 the unconditioned Self) comes. In the beginning, one may be in samadhi sta=
te now and then. As practice is perfected, one can be in it all the time an=
d become liberated.
=C2=A0
An unawkened sadhaka practicing bhakti yoga is d=
evoted to god and worships him/her as much as one can, but will project his=
 ego, conditioning and desires onto his worship and hence onto the god he w=
orships. For example, he may think "I worship the highest god while that pe=
rson worships a lower god. I am better" or "I am worshipping god everyday. =
I will get so and so result" or "I worship god more than that person. I am =
better". An awkened sadhaka practicing bhakti yoga has little expectation, =
pride etc. Worship becomes not about him but about god! He worships god and=
 marvels at the power that holds this cosmos together - the power that runs=
 things infinitismally smaller than a boson and infinitely larger than a ga=
laxy. He will look at himself as a fully insignificant particle in front a =
supreme power. His desires, likes, dislikes, conditioning and agendas start=
 to seem too insignificant in front of contemplating about that supreme pow=
er. Even as that
 devotional spirit increases, there will be episodes when =
one becomes self-centered in one's worship. But with practice, one loses on=
eself completely and surrenders completely to the supreme power and become =
liberated in the end.
=C2=A0
In each path, one may walk the path without ma=
king any significant progress for a long time. As one starts to imbibe the =
inherent qualities of the path, some internal transformation will kick in. =
Yet, the force of prior conditioning, coming from many lives, is too strong=
 to overcome. One keeps walking..
